"Hansen J., Ruedy R., Sato M., Reynolds R.","Global surface air temperature in 1995: Return to pre-Pinatubo level",1996,"Geophysical Research Letters","23","13",,"1665","1668",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030159411&partnerID=40&md5=1b199425520b953904615ca998668eba","NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; NOAA Natl. Ctr. Environ. Prediction, Camp Springs, MD, United States; NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; NOAA Natl. Ctr. Environ. Prediction, 5200 Auth Road, Camp Springs, MD 20746, United States","Hansen, J., NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States, NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Ruedy, R., NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States, NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Sato, M., NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States, NASA Goddard Inst. for Space Studies, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Reynolds, R., NOAA Natl. Ctr. Environ. Prediction, Camp Springs, MD, United States, NOAA Natl. Ctr. Environ. Prediction, 5200 Auth Road, Camp Springs, MD 20746, United States","Global surface air temperature has increased about 0.5°C from the minimum of mid-1992, a year after the Mt. Pinatubo eruption. Both a land-based surface air temperature record and a land-marine temperature index place the meteorological year 1995 at approximately the same level as 1990, previously the warmest year in the period of instrumental data. As El Niño warming was small in 1995, the solar cycle near a minimum, and ozone depletion near record levels, the observed high temperature supports the contention of an underlying global warming trend. The pattern of Northern Hemisphere temperature change in recent decades appears to reflect a change of atmospheric dynamics. Copyright 1996 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Air; Climate change; Drought; Global warming; Heat radiation; Meteorological problems; Oceanography; Solar radiation; Surfaces; Volcanoes; Atmospheric dynamics; El Nino warming; Global surface air temperature; Land based surface air temperature; Land marine temperature index; Marine temperatures; Mount Pinatubo eruption; Northern Hemisphere temperature; Pre-Pinatubo level; Atmospheric temperature; air temperature; El Nino warming; global surface; Mount Pinatubo; ozone depletion; solar cycle; temperature data (1995)",,,,,,"Bassett, G.W., Lin, Z., Breaking global temperature records after Mt. Pinatubo (1993) Clim. Change, 23, pp. 179-184; Deming, D., Climatic warming in North America: Analysis of borehole temperatures (1995) Science, 268, pp. 1576-1577; Broecker, W.S., Chaotic climate (1995) Sci. Amer., 273, pp. 62-68; Folland, C.K., Karl, T., Vinnikov, K.Y., (1992) Climate Change 1992, The IPCC Supplementary Report, 200p. , edited by J.T. Houghton, B.A. Callander, and S.K. Varney, Cambridge Univ. Press; Graham, N.B., Simulation of recent global temperature trends (1995) Science, 267, pp. 666-671; Hansen, J., Johnson, D., Lacis, A., Lebedeff, S., Lee, P., Rind, D., Russell, G., Climate impact of increasing atmospheric carbon dioxide (1981) Science, 213, pp. 957-966; Hansen, J., Lacis, A., Ruedy, R., Sato, M., Wilson, H., How sensitive is the world's climate? (1993) Nat. Geograph. Res. Explor., 9, pp. 142-158; Hansen, J., Lebedeff, S., Global trends of measured surface air temperature (1987) J. Ceophys. Res., 92, pp. 13,345-13,372. , HL87; Hansen, J., Lebedeff, S., Global surface air temperatures: Update through 1987 (1988) Geophys. Res. Lett., 15, pp. 323-326. , HL88; Trenberth, K.E., Hoar, T.J., The 1990-1995 El Niño-southern oscillation event: Longest on record (1996) Geophys. Res. Lett., 23, pp. 57-60; Wallace, J.M., Zhang, Y., Renwick, J.A., Dynamic contribution to hemispheric mean temperature trends (1995) Science, 270, pp. 780-783","Hansen, J